Part II - (Loan Data Exploration)¶

by (Ethel Elikem)¶

Investigation Overview¶

In this investigation, I wanted to look at the features of a loan that could be used to predict its final status. The main focus was on the borrower rate, loan amountemployment status.

Dataset Overview¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans from 2005 to 2014 with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

Categories of Loan Status¶

$50,000$ plus of loans in the dataset have a current status and close to $40,000$ are completed. Plotting on a log scale, shows the value of other loan status with count below $10,000$. Since current loans are not in a final status we focus on loans of other statuses.

Loan Status vs Employment status¶

Majority of the loans with completed status have borrowers with employment status of employed or full-time. This form more than half of the dataset.

Loan Status vs Loan Amount and Term¶

Most loans irrespective of amount and status have a term of $36$ months or $60$ months.

Loan Status vs Loan Amount and Borrower Rate¶

Borrower rate appears to be with the range $0.2 -0.4$ percent irrespective of loan amount with few loans having a borrower rate greater than $0.4$ percent.
